<subSubSection id="65A7652EC0734B11FF014E51FE4B3756" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2D0236A5C0734B11FF014E51FE4B3756" blockId="18.[192,1440,772,833]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FF014E51FE8B3709" bold="true" box="[192,316,772,798]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The very attractive color pattern of the elytra as depicted in 
<figureCitation id="B5862A20C0734B11FC264E51FB833709" box="[999,1076,772,798]" captionStart="Figures 82–85" captionStartId="61.[192,279,1859,1885]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1826]" captionTargetId="figure-38@61.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="Figures 82–85. Habitus of Axina species. 82) Axina adelosa. 83) A. bella. 84) A. bifasciata. 85) A. macilenta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565013/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 83</figureCitation>
will distinguish the members of this species from congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65A7652EC0734B11FF014E04FBEA30B5" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph id="2D0236A5C0734B11FF014E04FBEA30B5" blockId="18.[192,1441,849,1186]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FF014E04FEE5377C" bold="true" box="[192,338,849,875]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FE9A4E04FE31377C" box="[347,390,849,875]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Size</emphasis>
. Length 12.0 mm; width 3.0 mm. 
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FCD44E07FCE7377C" box="[789,848,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Form</emphasis>
. As in 
<figureCitation id="B5862A20C0734B11FC674E04FC40377C" box="[934,1015,849,875]" captionStart="Figures 82–85" captionStartId="61.[192,279,1859,1885]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1826]" captionTargetId="figure-38@61.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="Figures 82–85. Habitus of Axina species. 82) Axina adelosa. 83) A. bella. 84) A. bifasciata. 85) A. macilenta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565013/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 83</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FBC24E04FBF7377C" box="[1027,1088,849,875]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Color</emphasis>
. Cranium castaneous; antenna testaceous; prothorax bicolorous, venter and pronotal sides black; pronotal middle widely castaneous; pterothorax and legs black; elytra tricolorous, mostly yellow, humerus and epipleural margin widely black, black region extends broadly mesally towards sutural margin at elytral middle and at preapical region, black preapical region extends to sutural margin in form of fascia, apical region castaneous, castaneous region blends into more basal black fascia; abdomen testaceous. 
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FDF84EA8FDC33000" box="[569,628,1021,1047]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Head</emphasis>
. Cranium finely punctate, frons about as wide as length of antennal pedicel; EW/FW 60/13. 
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FE5F4975FE5B302D" box="[414,492,1056,1082]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum finely punctate, with 2 tumescences, concave at middle; PW/PL 110/155; elytra, few asetiferous punctures concentrated in elytral basal ½ proximal to sutural margin, width of interstitial spaces variable; EL/EW 475/90. 
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FDEB4930FD243068" box="[554,659,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="B5862A20C0734B11FCDD4930FCDB3097" box="[796,876,1125,1152]" captionStart="Figures 25–28" captionStartId="48.[194,281,1152,1178]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,719,1122]" captionTargetId="figure-65@48.[192,1440,719,1122]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figures 25–28. Aedeagi. 25) Axina bella. 26) A. ignota. 27) A. klisis. 28) A. luzia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564975" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564975/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
), phallobasic lobes very short, narrowly extended, contiguous; edge of phallic plates serrate; phallobasic apodeme slightly lengthened.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65A7652EC0734B11FF0149E7FB9930DB" box="[192,1070,1202,1229]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2D0236A5C0734B11FF0149E7FB9930DB" blockId="18.[192,1070,1202,1229]" box="[192,1070,1202,1229]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FF0149E7FEE430DB" bold="true" box="[192,339,1202,1228]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Distribution</emphasis>
(for map see 
<figureCitation id="B5862A20C0734B11FE2B49E7FD8F30DA" box="[490,568,1202,1229]" captionStart="Figure 69" captionStartId="54.[192,268,1865,1891]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-11@54.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="Figure 69. Distribution map for Axina species: A. atmis, A. bahia, A. brunnea, A. longevittata, A. diversesignata, A. lobispinula, A. orcastomata, A. plagiata, A. adelosa, A. bella, A. bifasciata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564999" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564999/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
). This species is known from 
<collectingCountry id="55AA7635C0734B11FC4049E7FB9C30DB" box="[897,1067,1202,1228]" name="French Guiana" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65A7652EC0734B11FF014988FDC6310E" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2D0236A5C0734B11FF014988FDC6310E" blockId="18.[191,1440,1245,1305]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FF014988FEF330E0" bold="true" box="[192,324,1245,1271]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName id="EABD4D26C0734B11FDE84988FDEA30E0" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[553,605,1245,1271]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bella">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FDE84988FDEA30E0" box="[553,605,1245,1271]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">bella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin adjective that stems from 
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C0734B11FC2D4988FB9C30E0" box="[1004,1067,1245,1271]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">bellus</emphasis>
(= beauty). I refer to the beautiful coloration of the dorsum of this beetle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
